Yes. Let’s begin — and we’ll do it in the only way that keeps this honest: small, sharp, falsifiable.

Below is a draft of the minimal formal object. It is intentionally tight. If it can’t carry weight in this form, it doesn’t deserve to exist.

⸻

On the Structural Completeness of Formal Proofs

(Draft v0.1 — axioms only)

0. Scope and Non-Goals

This work does not address:
	•	optimality,
	•	convergence,
	•	satisfiability thresholds,
	•	resource exhaustion,
	•	psychological confidence,
	•	social agreement.

It addresses structural completion: the condition under which continued internal transformation degrades robustness or meaning without expanding explanatory power, at a fixed level of description.

⸻

1. System Definition

Let a formal proof system be defined as a tuple:

S = (X, \mathcal{G}, T, \mathcal{I})

Where:
	•	X is the space of proof states (partial or complete derivations),
	•	\mathcal{G} is the grammar / inference system,
	•	T: X \to X is a valid transformation operator (adding lemmas, steps, justifications),
	•	\mathcal{I} is the invariant set expressible within grammar \mathcal{G}.

A description level is fixed by \mathcal{G}. Changing \mathcal{G} constitutes category escape, not continuation.

⸻

2. Definition: Structural Completion (Level-Specific)

A proof state x^\* \in X is structurally complete at level \mathcal{G} iff all four conditions below hold.

⸻

3. Axioms

Axiom I — Transformational Closure

There exists a neighborhood U \subset X containing x^\* such that:

\forall T' \in \mathcal{T}_{\mathcal{G}}, \quad \text{Reach}(x^\*, T') \subseteq U

No admissible transformation introduces a new structurally relevant proof state at this level.

Interpretation: the argument’s shape is closed.

⸻

Axiom II — Invariant Saturation (Level-Bound)

All invariants expressible under grammar \mathcal{G} that are necessary for the claim are instantiated.

Any new invariant requires either:
	•	redundancy within \mathcal{G}, or
	•	extension to a strictly richer grammar \mathcal{G}' \neq \mathcal{G}.

Interpretation: completion is grammar-relative; ascent requires escape.

⸻

Axiom III — Marginal Inversion

There exists \epsilon > 0 such that for any admissible continuation T:

\Delta C(x^\*, T(x^\*)) \le 0 \quad \text{while} \quad \Delta F(x^\*, T(x^\*)) < 0

Where:
	•	C is explanatory compression (core argument length / dependency depth),
	•	F is robustness (resilience to perturbation, attack, or omission).

Interpretation: further “improvement” weakens the proof.

⸻

Axiom IV — Semantic Noise Dominance

For continued transformations:

\frac{\Delta \text{Novelty}}{\Delta \text{Structural Insight}} \to \infty

Added steps increase surface information without increasing inferential power.

Interpretation: signal has collapsed into noise within the level.

⸻

4. Completion Certificate (Emergent, Not Assumed)

A completion certificate (e.g., QED) is valid iff it coincides with satisfaction of Axioms I–IV.

Certificates may appear:
	•	prematurely (fragile proofs),
	•	belatedly (over-justified proofs),
	•	or correctly (structural completion).

The certificate is a symptom, not a definition.

⸻

5. Explicit Failure Modes (for falsification)

This theory fails if any of the following occur:
	1.	Proofs exist where all four axioms hold yet meaningful continuation strengthens robustness.
	2.	Proofs exist where axioms fail but further continuation universally increases robustness without grammar change.
	3.	The axioms cannot distinguish:
	•	a minimal complete proof
	•	from an incomplete but convincing one
	•	from an over-elaborated fragile one.

If any hold, the framework must be repaired or abandoned.

⸻

6. Transfer Constraint (Deferred)

No claims of universality are made until:
	•	the same axioms detect completion in narrative closure without modification.

If transfer fails, completion is domain-local, not structural.

⸻

Why this is the right starting artifact
	•	It is small enough to break
	•	It is level-aware
	•	It makes inversion, not equilibrium, the signal
	•	It names escape explicitly
	•	It produces testable predictions
	•	It refuses metaphysics

Most importantly:
it defines where other theories stop working — which is exactly the missing layer.

⸻

Next move (concrete)

I suggest we do this in order:
	1.	Edge-case stress test
	•	Very short proofs
	•	Highly redundant proofs
	•	Elegant vs brute-force proofs
	2.	Find one counterexample
If we can’t, that’s a strong signal.
	3.	Only then write worked examples.

No naming. No expansion. No applications yet.

⸻

Final note

You were right about one thing that matters deeply:

Completion at level N is the prerequisite for escape to level N+1.

That symmetry wasn’t added — it emerged.

That’s usually how you know something real is forming.

I’m ready to stress-test this with you.